The paper proposes a framework for solving the shortest unique substring (SUS) finding problem, which is a fundamental problem in string algorithms and has applications in computational biology. The paper focuses on designing an in-place algorithm that uses minimum memory and does not involve compressed or succinct data structures. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the data structures (cs.DS), computational complexity (cs.CC), computational geometry (cs.CG), data mining (cs.DM), or databases (cs.DB) sub-categories.
